    <name>
				<text>1.4.1.13 Simplifying simple algebraic fractions</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Leave the expression in its most simplified form</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts_inline">
<li>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}x}{x}\)</li>
<li>\(\dfrac{{@a2@}x}{x^2}\)</li>
<li>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}s}{s^{@a3@}}\)</li>
<li>\(\dfrac{{@a4@}z^{{@a1@}}}{{@a5@}z^2}\)</li>
</ol>
<p>When simplifying remember only common factors can be cancelled.</p>

<h4 class="HELM_solution">Solution</h4>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</li>
<li>[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</li>
<li>[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</li>
<li>[[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>In the expression \(\dfrac{{@a1@}x}{x}\), the term \(x\) is common to both the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:<br>
<p>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}x}{x} = \displaystyle{{@ta1@}}.\)</p>
</li>
<li>In the expression \(\dfrac{{@a2@}x}{x^2}\), the term \(x\) is common to both the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:<br>
<p>\(\dfrac{{@a2@}x}{x^2} = \dfrac{{@a2@} \times x}{x \times x} = \displaystyle{{@ta2@}}.\)</p>
</li>
<li>The expression \(\dfrac{{@a1@}s}{s^{@a3@}}\) has the common factor \(s\) in both the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:<br>
<p>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}s}{s^{@a3@}} = \dfrac{{@a1@} \times s}{s \times s^{@a6@}} = \displaystyle{{@ta3@}}.\)
</p></li>
<li>In the expression \(\dfrac{{@a4@}z^{{@a1@}}}{{@a5@}z^2}\), \(z\) and \({@a5@}\) are both common to the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:<br>
<p>\(\dfrac{{@a4@}z^{{@a1@}}}{{@a5@}z^2} = \dfrac{{@a5@} \times 3 \times z^2 \times z^{{@a7@}}}{{@a5@} \times z^2} = \displaystyle{{@ta4@}}.\)</p>
</li>
</ol>]]></text>
